<subSubSection id="76F01B726A091243EBD35B74044BBC7D" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="07D7BA5456D3C97F520B23AD9CE9F1A6" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F1E774D678D6B034507C91003403C998" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Rather similar to 
<taxonomicName id="52CB8DF36E9A4AC4092D1374A2F4B027" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dumetorum">
<emphasis id="B506C33C474AF5E04D44F9597D2BBF99" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea dumetorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but perennial with tuberous roots and a larger corolla reaching 4.5 cm in length. The leaves are also more strongly sagittate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="73FE093F5356F0BABF013D64F50F1106" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">This is the source of &quot;Tampico Jalap&quot;.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
